NBA Shot Selection Analysis¶

Vatsal Baherwani and Joseph Vincent

Introduction¶

The NBA is the world's largest basketball league, generating over $10 billion in revenue every year. It is also the 3rd overall largest sports league in the world. Teams are put under great pressure to win games, as this determines the popularity and success of each franchise. The most successful teams get an opportunity to compete in the NBA playoffs, which sell high-demand tickets and attract millions of TV viewers, resulting in additional millions of dollars of revenue. Teams are incentivized to win as many games as possible, but it is very hard to win in this league, and even harder to sustain winning teams over multiple seasons. Thus, it is in the interest of teams to figure out how to score the ball efficiently and frequently to put themselves in the best situation to win.

We will walk you through an analysis of shot selection in the NBA for the 2022-23 regular season. We will be analyzing the types of shots that are most successful and the shots and other factors that are correlated to winning games. We will also explore specific situations, such as: what are common shots taken towards the end of games, what types of shots are taken by the best players, what shots correspond to high scoring games, etc.

Collecting Data¶

We collect data from BasketballReference describing per-game stats for every player in the 2022-23 NBA season.

In [ ]:
response = requests.get('https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_2023_per_game.html')
parsed = BeautifulSoup(response.text)
tbl = parsed.body.find(id='per_game_stats').prettify()
pergamestats = pd.read_html(tbl)[0]

We also use NBA API (which scrapes stats.nba.com) to collect data for shot charts and game logs. Shot charts will show locations of every shot taken by players, and the game log describes each of the 1230 games played during the season along with box score stats. To avoid overloading the API and potentially getting blacklisted, we only request once and save the data in a JSON file.

For some background on shot charts and how they can help us understand basketball games, see: https://hoop-social.com/the-leagues-wildest-shot-charts-in-2022-23/

Processing Data¶

The BasketballReference website repeats the column names every 20 rows for ease of viewing, but we will drop these. Also, if a player is on multiple teams they have multiple rows in the dataset, with the first one representing their overall stats. So, we keep that first row out of all the duplicates.

In [ ]:
pergamestats.drop(pergamestats[pergamestats.Player == 'Player'].index, inplace=True)
pergamestats.drop_duplicates(subset=['Player'], keep='first', inplace=True)
pergamestats.reset_index(inplace=True)
pergamestats.drop(columns=['index', 'Rk'], inplace=True) # we don't need these anymore

Some stats will have N/A values if there are no such events (for example, N/A FTA if a player never attempted a free throw). This is the same as saying they just shot 0 free throws.

In [ ]:
pergamestats.fillna(0, inplace=True)

Now that our data is cleaned up, we will convert the types of every column to int or float. Note that this is done because we read from an HTML table which assumes string types. This is not necessary for our NBA API tables because those were loaded from JSON.

In [ ]:
for column in pergamestats.columns[6:]:
    pergamestats[column] = pergamestats[column].astype(float)

pergamestats.Age = pergamestats.Age.astype(int)
pergamestats.G = pergamestats.G.astype(int)
pergamestats.GS = pergamestats.GS.astype(int)

Looking at the shot chart data below: since the location coordinates in our shot chart are very granular (0.1 foot increments), let's round them by a factor of 5 to minimize the empty groups when we calculate accuracy. This will be useful when we want to look at aggregate statistics for certain spots on the court, as it will avoid empty spots due to a lack of data from that specific point.

In [ ]:
shotchart['ROUND_LOC_X'] = np.round(shotchart.LOC_X / 5) * 5
shotchart['ROUND_LOC_Y'] = np.round(shotchart.LOC_Y / 5) * 5

We want the shot chart data to be connected to these player stats, so we will merge based on player name. We will also create a dataframe merging the shot chart data with team data, so we can compare the shot selection of winning and losing teams. For this second merged dataframe, we also want to merge on game ID so that we can observe shot charts for specific games.

In [ ]:
playershotchart = shotchart.merge(pergamestats, how='left', left_on='PLAYER_NAME', right_on='Player')
teamshotchart = shotchart.merge(gamelog, how='left', on=['GAME_ID', 'TEAM_NAME'])

Some of the names won't match when we construct our player shot chart. Since we did a left join, let's see which of the right side Player variables didn't match. These mismatches happen mostly because of leaving out Jr./Sr/III in the name, or accents on some of the letters. To address this, we will use a string similarity metric called the Levenshtein distance to find the closest possible match for these names in the shot chart dataset. This process is also referred to as "fuzzy string searching".

Read more about this metric here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levenshtein_distance

Learn more about fuzzy string searching here: https://redis.com/blog/what-is-fuzzy-matching/

Let's verify that the names match reasonably. We also want to create a mapping to update the right dataset names to match the left ones.

In [ ]:
def find_closest_match(name, choices):
    matches = fuzzywuzzy.process.extract(name, choices)
    return matches[0][0]

# find best match for every name
matches = [find_closest_match(name, pergamestats.Player) for name in missingnames]
matchesdf = pd.DataFrame({'Missing Name': missingnames, 'Match': matches})
display(matchesdf)

# zip to create pairs, and turn it into a mapping
missingnamesmap = dict(zip(matches, missingnames))
pergamestats.loc[pergamestats.Player.isin(matches), 'Player'] = pergamestats.loc[pergamestats.Player.isin(matches), 'Player'].map(missingnamesmap)

Exploratory Data Analysis + Data Visualization¶

We will look at Effective Field Goal Percentage, or eFG%, which weights the 3 point shot percentage by 1.5 since it counts for more points. Across the NBA, the eFG% follows a normal distribution. The league-wide mean is roughly 55%.

For more information about eFG% as a metric and why it is so important to winning, see: https://www.breakthroughbasketball.com/stats/effective-field-goal-percentage.html

In [ ]:
stat, p = scipy.stats.normaltest(pergamestats['eFG%'])
print(f'Normality t-statistic: {stat:0.2f}; p-value: {p}')

n, bins, patches = plt.hist(pergamestats['eFG%'], density=True, bins=50)
mean, std = scipy.stats.norm.fit(pergamestats['eFG%'])
plt.plot(bins, scipy.stats.norm.pdf(bins, mean, std), c='orange')

plt.title('eFG% Distribution')
plt.xlabel('eFG%')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

Normality t-statistic: 175.82; p-value: 6.615349793997254e-39

This normal distribution has fat tails, largely because of the outliers. What do these outliers look like in the data? It turns out that these are very small sample sizes i.e. the players only played a few games and either shot really well or really poorly. In the following analysis, we will want to filter for players that played a decent amount of games.

We define rotation players as players that played at least 20 games in the season, and averaged at least 12 minutes a game (25% of the full 48 minutes). These are the players that are in the general rotation of 5-man lineups that coaches cycle through, so we can be sure that they have an ample amount of shot attempts to calculate eFG%. Now the eFG% distribution is much smoother, and we see the steep drop-off of players averaging an eFG% above about 57%.

Now we will look at the shot chart data. Let's begin by visualizing what shot charts look like for certain players. The shot data is relative to the rim, which is 6 feet away from the edge of the court, so we offset the Y coordinate by 60 to fit into the court drawing.

To learn more about NBA court dimensions and the numbers that we use in this drawing, see: https://official.nba.com/rule-no-1-court-dimensions-equipment/

In [ ]:
# Source for coordinates: https://www.kaggle.com/code/ubiratanfilho/creating-nba-shot-charts
def draw_court():
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5*1.5, 4.7*1.5))
    color='black'

    ax.plot([-220, -220], [0, 140], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.plot([220, 220], [0, 140], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.add_artist(mpl.patches.Arc((0, 140), 440, 315, theta1=0, theta2=180, facecolor='none', edgecolor=color, lw=1))


    ax.plot([-80, -80], [0, 190], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.plot([80, 80], [0, 190], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.plot([-60, -60], [0, 190], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.plot([60, 60], [0, 190], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.plot([-80, 80], [190, 190], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.add_artist(mpl.patches.Circle((0, 190), 60, facecolor='none', edgecolor=color, lw=1))
    ax.plot([-250, 250], [0, 0], linewidth=1, color=color)
    ax.plot([-250, 250], [470, 470], linewidth=1, color=color)

    ax.add_artist(mpl.patches.Circle((0, 60), 15, facecolor='none', edgecolor=color, lw=1))
    ax.plot([-30, 30], [40, 40], linewidth=1, color=color)

    ax.set_xticks([])
    ax.set_yticks([])

    ax.set_xlim(-250, 250)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 470)

    return fig, ax

Given the high volume of shots taken throughout an 82-game, plotting every single one is not insightful. We will instead use a hexbin plot that will filter for locations that multiple shots are taken from (at least 2). Also, the bins will be labeled by their log frequency. In the plot below, green and yellow represent high frequency shots for 2x MVP point guard Stephen Curry.

In [ ]:
def shot_frequency_chart(chart, title, mincnt=2):
    fig, ax = draw_court()
    # 50 by 50 hex grid, bounded by our court dimensions
    hexbin = ax.hexbin(chart.LOC_X, chart.LOC_Y + 60, cmap='viridis', bins='log', gridsize=50, mincnt=mincnt, extent=(-250, 250, 422.5, -47.5))

    # create colorbar with 3 tick labels
    cbaxes = inset_axes(ax, width="3%", height="30%", loc=1) 
    cb = plt.colorbar(plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='viridis'), cax=cbaxes, label='Freq', orientation='vertical')
    cb.set_ticks([0, 0.5, 1])
    cb.set_ticklabels(['Low', 'Mid', 'High'])

    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.show()

Let's now look at shot accuracy across the court. This is where we will use the rounded locations computed above, because we will be aggregating overall accuracy from every spot, not just frequency. The average of the SHOT_MADE_FLAG equals the number of shots made divided by the number of shots taken, so that will be our accuracy metric. It is evident that overall shot accuracy tapers off with distance. Additionally, long 2-pointers are less accurate than 3-pointers. The most accurate shots other than layups are mid-range shots, and we also see that midrange shots from the corner are less accurate than from any other angle.

In [ ]:
def shot_accuracy_chart(chart, title):
    shot_accuracy = chart.groupby(['ROUND_LOC_X', 'ROUND_LOC_Y']).SHOT_MADE_FLAG.mean().reset_index()

    fig, ax = draw_court()
    # larger grid, adjust alpha so we don't color over the court lines
    hexbin = ax.hexbin(chart.ROUND_LOC_X, chart.ROUND_LOC_Y + 60, C=chart.SHOT_MADE_FLAG, cmap='plasma', bins=20, gridsize=32, alpha=0.8, mincnt=1, edgecolors=None, extent=(-250, 250, 422.5, -47.5))

    cbaxes = inset_axes(ax, width="3%", height="30%", loc=1) 
    cb = plt.colorbar(plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='plasma'), cax=cbaxes, label='Accuracy', orientation='vertical')
    cb.set_ticks([0, 0.5, 1])
    cb.set_ticklabels(['Low', 'Mid', 'High'])

    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.show()
In [ ]:
shot_accuracy_chart(shotchart, 'NBA Shot Accuracy')

This is data from the entire NBA, but let's look at the highest and most efficient scorers. These are individuals who are top-tier scorers, and who are efficient. We first want players that average at least 20 points per game on over 8 field goal attempts, showing that these are high volume scorers. We also want players who consistently perform, so we are limiting the games started to over 41, which is half of the 82-game regular season. To get the efficient scorers, we are sorting by effective field goal percentage. Recall that effective field goal percentage weights field goal percentage for 3-pointers, counting them as 1.5 shot attempts, because they count for more points. This ensures we are not leaving out high-volume shooters whose field goal percentage is low because they are attempting more 3s than individuals who do not take those shots.

From this shot chart, we can see that in contrast to the rest of the NBA, these individuals do not take long 2-point shots, and they make mid-range shots at a much higher rate than the rest of the NBA. We see this by comparing mid-range shot accuracy to the league-wide accuracy from the chart above. Some of these spots are the elbow, free-throw line, and low-post areas. This might mean that these players are very efficient at scoring from isolation plays which can begin in these areas, or that due to the spacing created by calling mid-range shots inefficient, there is actually a lot of room between the 3-point line and paint, that these efficient top scorers use to their advantage.

We also see that shots from the right side of the court i.e. the left side from the players' perspective have an increased accuracy as opposed to the other side. This makes sense as most people are naturally right-handed, so shooting a pull-up jump shot may be more comfortable than driving all the way to the rim for a left-handed layup when the player is on that side of the court.

Modeling the Data¶

The following 4 models, show the effect of Field Goal %, 3-Pt Field Goal %, Defensive Rebounds, and Assists on +/-. We chose Field Goal % and 3-Pt Field Goal % since we saw earlier that these factors may be correlated with winning more games. Likewise, defensive rebounds are a factor that many NBA analysts have said decides games. Since strong defensive rebounding limits the amount of extra possessions a team earns, it can also limit the opposition's points heavily, helping teams win more games. Finally, a large number of assists may mean that more high quality shots are being created which may lead to higher field goal percentages and other high shooting attributes.

Field Goal percentage is correlated with winning. The summary shows a p-value of 0, meaning that it is statistically significant and is impactful in predicting which team wins. As a result, we can conclude that it's very important for teams to look for high quality shot attempts to keep their field goal percentage high. Specifically, it is important for teams to shoot in the areas that they are known to shoot well from like the areas in the shot charts we analyzed earlier, which may lead to a high field goal percentage.

In [ ]:

Let's now use these factors which we know are correlated with winning in constructing a general prediction model for team +/-. We will try to predict the 2022 NBA champion Golden State Warriors' performance throughout this current season. We start by constructing a dataset excluding the Warriors, so that the Warriors games are out-of-sample. Then we will run a multivariate OLS regression including each of FG%, 3FG%, DREB, and AST as factors. The model does a fairly accurate job of predicting the Warriors +/- given the other variables of these games. However, what we really care about is whether they won or not. We compare the sign of the +/- (1 in a win, -1 in a loss) and find that our OLS regression is roughly 82% accurate in predicting Warriors wins.

In [ ]:
# separate warriors games, and all other games by dropping warriors games
warriors = gamelog[gamelog.TEAM_ABBREVIATION == 'GSW']
predmodel = sma.formula.ols('PLUS_MINUS ~ FG_PCT + FG3_PCT + DREB + AST', data = gamelog.drop(warriors.index)).fit()

plt.plot(pd.to_datetime(warriors.GAME_DATE), warriors.PLUS_MINUS, label='True +/-')

ypred = predmodel.predict(sma.add_constant(warriors[['FG_PCT', 'FG3_PCT', 'DREB', 'AST']]))
plt.plot(pd.to_datetime(warriors.GAME_DATE), ypred, label='Predicted +/-')
plt.xlabel('Game Date')
plt.ylabel('Plus-Minus')
plt.title('Golden State Warriors +/- Predictions')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# on average, how often did we get the win prediction correct?
model_accuracy = (np.sign(warriors.PLUS_MINUS) == np.sign(ypred)).mean() * 100
print(f'Win prediction accuracy: {model_accuracy:0.2f}%')

Win prediction accuracy: 81.71%

We claimed above that high 3-point shooting frequency and accuracy were part of the recipe for winning games. We visualize this relationship below, and use a Support Vector Machine to fit a boundary that distinguishes winning and losing as accurately as possible. We map wins and losses to the values 0 and 1 respectively, and fit a function taking in the 2-dimensional data of 3 point attempts and 3 point percentage as input. To plot these points, we group by X and Y values (since attempts are a discrete amount) and find the average winning percentage for those circumstances. The colors represent the win percentage for that data point, i.e. red represents always losing, green represents always winning, and yellow represents somewhere in between.

As expected, teams that shoot at both a high rate and high accuracy (1 standard deviation above the mean) are very likely to win games. We see this from the level curve drawn on the top right, representing the boundary for a prediction of 1 (win). However, a much higher percentage is required to win consistently if a team takes few attempts. At the same time, teams can get away with lower accuracy if they shoot a high volume of 3-pointers. We see this from the middle boundary representing the midpoint value of 0.5. This is a downward sloping line, which means teams can make up for poor shooting percentages with increased frequency, and vice versa.

To learn more about Support Vector Machines see: https://towardsdatascience.com/support-vector-machine-introduction-to-machine-learning-algorithms-934a444fca47?gi=049569c0381a

In our exploratory data analysis, we made multiple claims about certain spots on the court being more efficient to shoot from than others. Here we will justify those claims using K-Means clustering. This is a method that allows us to separate spatial data into distinct groups based on the concentration of points in every group. We will start off by clustering 3-point shots on the court and limiting them to 32 feet or less to prevent longer shots, which are uncommon, from skewing the percentages.

You can read more about K-means clustering here: https://neptune.ai/blog/k-means-clustering

In [ ]:
shotchart3pt = playershotchart[(shotchart.SHOT_TYPE == '3PT Field Goal') & (shotchart.SHOT_DISTANCE < 32)].copy()

kmeans = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=7)
kmeans.fit(shotchart3pt[['LOC_X', 'LOC_Y']])

labels = kmeans.labels_
centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_

# assign cluster to every shot chart point
shotchart3pt['cluster'] = labels

fig, ax = draw_court()
ax.scatter(shotchart3pt.LOC_X, shotchart3pt.LOC_Y + 60, c=labels)
ax.scatter(centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1] + 60, marker='D', s=60, linewidths=3, color='white')

# label centroids by number
for i in range(centroids.shape[0]):
    plt.text(centroids[i, 0], centroids[i, 1] + 60, i, ha='center', va='center', fontweight='bold')

plt.title('NBA 3-point Shot Clustering')
plt.show()

Let's analyze the average FG% from each of these clusters throughout the season. We find that the most efficient 3-pointers by a long shot are in clusters which correspond to corner 3-pointers, the shortest 3-point shot. This supports the hypothesis that we had before claiming that corner 3s would be more efficient. Interestingly, the worst shots are from the top of the 3-point line. These shots are made at nearly a 4% lower rate than corner 3 point shots.

Let's now apply the same method that we discussed regarding the eFG% metric. 3-pointers are worth 1.5x as much as 2-pointers, so we want to weight the shot percentage for those accordingly in order to reasonably compare them to 2-pointers. Now we can see clusters with the best overall efficiency. Aside from shots right under the basket, every type of 3-pointer is more efficient than any other 2-pointer. Recall that the most efficient shooting teams, along with the highest scoring teams, focused on strictly 3-pointers and shots in the paint. We now see statistical evidence supporting this decision. The highest percentage 2-pointer outside of a layup falls at a 46% rate on average. The worst 3-pointer statistically is made roughly 35% of the time.

Interpreting the Data¶

Insight/Decisions: As seen throughout our analysis, the kind of shots teams and players take matters. With data from the NBA API and Basketball Reference, we can see that shooting from different areas and the ability to take and make good shots at a high rate are what separates good players from great players. The more points a team scores the more likely they are to win games, so teams have to prioritize taking good high percentage shots. 3s in the corner, shots in the paint, and mid-range shots away from the baseline tend to be great places for teams to shoot from, so teams potentially need to work on these kinds of shots more. Other factors like defensively rebounding well and passing the ball are also very important to the outcome of games. Our model of combined factors such as field goal percentage, 3 point field goal percentage, defensive rebounding, and assists was able to accurately predict the outcome of recent games for teams such as Golden State, and shows that there is a clear need for teams to emphasize these points of play in their gameplans. While our analysis does not take into account all factors of basketball, it does show that shooting more 3s and playing a strong team game with good fundamentals is what wins games. Analysts tend to use the phrase "passing the eye-test" for teams that pass well and take high percentage shots. Our analysis shows this is indeed correlated with winning basketball. Our analysis also shows that inefficient shot-taking and shot-hunting hurts teams in the long run, and that some players who are glorified as great shot-creators may in fact be hurting their teams, because of their inefficiencies.

We hope that reading this tutorial about NBA shooting and shot charts inspires you to learn more about basketball and data science, and we hope you tune in to the rest of the NBA playoffs!
